          "body": "The oracle Ahijah delivers follows the structural logic of a covenant-lawsuit, a pattern traceable throughout the prophets (cf. Micah 6:1-8; Isaiah 1:2-20). It opens with a rehearsal of divine grace — 'I exalted you from among the people and made you leader over My people Israel, and tore the kingdom away from the house of David and gave it to you' (14:7-8). Every element of Jeroboam's kingship was God's gift, unearned and unsolicited. That foundation makes the sin that follows not merely political failure but personal betrayal. The indictment in verse 9 has three elements: making other gods and molten images, provoking God to anger, and casting God behind his back. The final phrase is the most damning — 'cast Me behind your back' (shalakh... gav) — a gesture of deliberate, contemptuous rejection. You do not accidentally cast someone behind your back; you choose to turn away. The sentence that follows (14:10-11) is total: every male in the dynasty cut off, the house swept away like dung, the dead denied honorable burial. The completeness of the judgment corresponds to the completeness of the rejection."
