        "title": "The God who sees through disguise — prophetic omniscience and Jeroboam's futile stratagem",
        "range": "14:1-6",
        "excerpt": "Come in, wife of Jeroboam, why do you pretend to be another woman? For I am sent to you with a harsh message.",
        "body": "The opening scene stages one of the Bible's most pointed dramatic ironies. Jeroboam, who has already rejected the Levitical priesthood and installed his own unauthorized cult (1 Kings 12:26-33), nevertheless turns to a true prophet of Yahweh when crisis hits home. This is not a contradiction but a portrait of functional paganism: the idolater who still treats Yahweh as a resource to be consulted, not as a Lord to be obeyed. Jeroboam does not repent, does not dismantle the golden calves, does not go himself. He sends a proxy in disguise, as if Ahijah were an oracle who could be managed by controlling the information he received.\n\nThe narrator underlines Ahijah's physical blindness precisely here (14:4) to set up the contrast: the man who cannot see with his natural eyes is told by God exactly what is happening before it happens. The Lord's advance briefing to Ahijah (14:5) is a cameo of prophetic epistemology throughout Scripture — the prophet knows not because he is clever but because Yahweh discloses. Jeremiah 23:18 asks: 'Who has stood in the council of the LORD, that he should see and hear His word?' Ahijah has. The wife of Jeroboam, for all her disguise, has not.\n\nWhen Ahijah speaks her name across the threshold (14:6), the word rendered 'pretend to be another woman' is the verb *nakhar* in the Hithpael stem — to make oneself unrecognizable, to disguise oneself. The prophet's question is rhetorical and devastating: 'Why do you make yourself unrecognizable?' The disguise was never a factor in what God sees. Tim Keller (Hidden Christmas, 2016) observes that God consistently approaches human concealment not by pretending not to see it but by naming it plainly — this is grace, not merely omniscience, because only named sin can be addressed. Ahijah names her sin before she speaks a word.\n\nThe phrase 'I am sent to you with a harsh message' (*qasheh*) establishes the prophet's authority: he is not an entrepreneur of bad news but a commissioned messenger. The harshness belongs to the message's content, not to Ahijah's temperament. The scene sets up the oracle that follows by establishing: (a) God's knowledge is perfect and prior; (b) human disguise is futile; (c) the prophet speaks under divine commission, not personal initiative.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nakhar* (Hithpael: to disguise oneself, make oneself unrecognizable) appears in 14:5 and 14:6. *Qasheh* (harsh, hard, severe) — the same root used for Pharaoh's hardened heart and for the 'hard bondage' of Egypt. The word signals that what follows is not pastoral counsel but judicial verdict."
